author: Xyla Foxlin
description:
My rocket hit Mach 2.2—but there was no sonic boom. 🤔 How? This is Spite, my all-carbon supersonic rocket that reached 23,000 ft, and today we’re diving into the science of why you didn’t hear the “boom.” From shock waves and Mach cones to doppler effects and “boom carpets,” we’re breaking down how sonic booms actually work—and why rockets that go straight up can stay completely silent. It’s physics, engineering, and chaos—all at Mach 2.

Watch the full video to learn how sound, shock, and supersonic flight collide (literally).
